Mandatory access control: s-e-linux and app-armor.

The permissions you learned earlier, owner, group, and other, controlled with change-mode, are known formally as discretionary access control. The word discretionary means that the file's owner decides who may access it. That is enough for most situations, but not for defence in depth: if a web server is compromised, ordinary discretionary permissions let the attacker do everything the web server's own user could do, which may be a great deal.

Mandatory access control adds a second, independent layer. On top of the ordinary permissions, the kernel also consults a security policy, and crucially, even root is constrained by it. Two implementations matter on linux. S-e-linux is the default on the red hat family; it works by labelling every file and process and defining rules about which labels may interact, which is powerful but complex. App-armor is the default on ubuntu and the suse family; it uses path-based profiles, one per program, and is simpler to read and write. At this level you do not need to author policies; you need to know that these systems exist, how to check their state, how to switch them on or off, and how to read a denial message.

Take s-e-linux as the example. It has three modes. Enforcing means denials are actually blocked, which is the production setting. Permissive means denials are logged but not blocked, which is invaluable for troubleshooting, because you can see what would have been denied without anything actually breaking. And disabled means it is switched off entirely. You can read the current mode with get-enforce and switch temporarily between enforcing and permissive with set-enforce, while a permanent change, including fully disabling it, is made in its configuration file and requires a reboot. The single most useful habit when a service mysteriously fails on a red hat system is to remember that mandatory access control might be the cause, flip to permissive to test, and check the denial logs.
